<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="351" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="351">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="351">
Among the more than twenty specimens of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Abacomorphus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Abacomorphus caledonicus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="351" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caledonicus">Abacomorphus caledonicus</taxonomicName>
I examined there is significant variation in size, color and to a lesser degree microsculpturing. However, male genitalia were very uniform. This contrasts with 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Abacoleptus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Abacoleptus asperulus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="351" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="asperulus">Abacoleptus asperulus</taxonomicName>
, which had little variation in size and color.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
